The init command creates .drift/ (containing state.xml and baselines/), and if main.drift.xml does not already exist, writes a starter template with a single example spec. It also creates .drift/.gitignore containing "user-settings.xml" to prevent accidental commits of per-user theme preferences. The output message instructs the user to edit main.drift.xml, place markers, and run drift skill. Init is NOT idempotent: if .drift/state.xml already exists (the project is already initialized), init FAILS with an error message instructing the user that the project is already initialized and that re-running init would overwrite existing state. The error mentions the state.xml path and exits with code 1. See init_idempotent for the orchestrator-level enforcement. To forcibly reinitialize, the user must delete .drift/state.xml (or .drift/) by hand — drift provides no command to do this, by design (protecting against accidental state loss).